    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-18T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="12"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d12">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.24/57: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-18T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 18, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>575. Your 779, May 16, 9 a.m. Department appreciates General Maxwell’s
                    suggestion. You and he will be glad to know that before receipt of your message
                    Fred Winant had been selected as civilian representative. He will probably leave
                    around July 1 accompanied by an administrative assistant with Lend-Lease
                    accounting training. Both will be appointed in the Foreign Service
                    Auxiliary.</p>
                <p>It is planned to designate Winant “United States Civilian Representative on the
                    MESC” and to attach him to the Missions at Cairo, Baghdad, Tehran and Jiddah so
                    that he may have the benefit of the advice of the respective Chiefs of Mission.
                    Department would appreciate your comment on this as well as your reply to the
                    following: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>What additional staff if any do you think it would be desirable for
                            Winant to have?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Could the Legation provide him with a competent secretary or should
                            one accompany him?</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Could Jacobs or Jones assist Winant to some extent, particularly
                            during latter’s absence from Cairo?</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>British Food Ministry has suggested that he be accompanied by an
                            agricultural expert to advise on new crop plantings. Do you consider
                            this advisable?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For public statement regarding purpose and membership of Middle East Supply
                        Center, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, January 16,
                        1943, page 76.]</p>
                </postscript>
